	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>MEPs vote to defer deadline for EPA negotiations to 2016</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 October 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 12 September 2012, the European Parliament adopted a resolution by 322 votes to 78 (with 218 abstentions) to defer the deadline for the completion of the EPA negotiations process until 1 January 2016. This potentially means that non-LDC ACP country exporters whose governments fail to conclude the EPA negotiation process would now only lose duty-free, quota-free access to the EU market on 1 January 2016 rather than 1 January 2014, as initially proposed by the EC. The vote primarily affects 8 non-LDCs – Botswana, Cameroon, Fiji, Ghana, Côte d’Ivoire, Kenya, Namibia and Swaziland. Least developed countries would not be affected, since they already have duty-free, quota-free access to the EU market under the EU’s ‘Everything but Arms’ initiative.</p><p>In the debate, MEPs took the view that while ‘unlimited and unconditional preferences’ were not a sustainable option, they felt that the EU should provide ACP governments with ‘a realistic timeframe to work towards fair and development-focused EPAs’. Some MEPs argued that ‘no ACP country should be forced to sign an unsatisfactory EPA,’ since ‘this is not the trade and development relationship [the EU] should have.’</p><p>Dr Mohamed Ibn Chambas, Secretary General of the ACP, described the vote in the European Parliament as ‘prudent’, highlighting the complexities of the EPA negotiation process and ‘the well founded reasons why the agreements reached in 2007 have not been concluded’. In particular, he highlighted the adverse effects that implementing bilaterally concluded agreements had on regional integration efforts.</p><p>The Secretary General argued that the negotiation process ‘requires careful and thorough discussions, without the pressure of unreasonable deadlines’. He noted earlier calls from the European Parliament for the EC to ‘show flexibility in the negotiation process’ and expressed the hope ‘that the Commission will demonstrate such flexibility in order to resolve the outstanding issues between now and 2016’.</p><p>One example of concerns in the countries affected prior to the European Parliament vote came from Kenyan flower exporters, who would face an average duty of 16% if current duty-free, quota-free access were lost. This is seen as particularly challenging in view of the arrival of new competitors from Latin America on the EU market. Kenya is seen as being in a particularly delicate position, as its regional interim EPA concluded with the EU includes four LCD partners who are also members of the EAC Customs Union. The Kenyan government for its part fears a loss of investment to neighbouring EAC countries whose exporters would continue to enjoy duty-free, quota-free access to the EU market under the EBA initiative if a full EPA were not concluded.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>European Parliament, ‘Don´t rush least developed countries into partnership agreements, say MEPs’, 13 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/pressroom/content/20120907IPR50828/html/Don%C2%B4t-rush-least-developed-countries-into-partnership-agreements-say-MEPs" target="_self">http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/pressroom/content/20120907IPR50828...</a></p><p>ACP Secretariat, ‘ACP Secretary General reacts to European Parliament vote on Market Access Regulation 1528/2007’, 13 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.acp.int/content/press-release-acp-secretary-general-reacts-european-parliament-vote-market-access-regulation" target="_self">http://www.acp.int/content/press-release-acp-secretary-general-reacts-eu...</a></p><p>ACP Secretariat, ‘EU Parliament debates ACP-EU free trade agreement deadline’, 12 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.acp.int/content/eu-parliament-debates-acp-eu-free-trade-agreement-deadline" target="_self">http://www.acp.int/content/eu-parliament-debates-acp-eu-free-trade-agree...</a></p><p><i>Fresh Talk</i>, ‘Kenyan flower sector in jeopardy as EU considers EPA deadline’, Issue no. 4, pp. 7–8 of PDF, September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.sl-systems.org/resources/Fresh%20Talk%20Issue%204%20Sept%202012.pdf" target="_self">http://www.sl-systems.org/resources/Fresh%20Talk%20Issue%204%20Sept%2020...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While ACP governments have welcomed the vote in the plenary session of the European Parliament, this is by no means the end of the EU decision-making process regarding the EC’s proposals to amend Market Access Regulation 1528/2007. The European Council - i.e. the EU member states’ ministers – will now have their say on the EC’s proposal. It remains to be seen what will be the outcome of the trilateral dialogue process to be launched by the Cyprus presidency. A trilateral dialogue process involves the European Commission, the European Council and the European Parliament in discussions to achieve a consensus.</p>
		</div>
		
